It's not clear what output is coming from where in your "importing process:" information given `cd..` is not a valid python command.

Running `help(rt)` after `import onnxruntime as rt` will provide details of the onnxruntime module that was loaded so you can check it's coming from the expected location.

Your build command line didn't have `--build_wheel` so it would not be building the python wheel with the onnxruntime python module.

Once the build completes with that addition, to use the onnxruntime python package without installing it via something like pip you'd need to change to the build output directory (e.g. build/Linux/RelWithDebInfo). That should have an 'onnxruntime' directory for the python package, which will have subdirectories called capi, backend and quantization amongst others. When you run python from the build output directory 'import onnxruntime' will load from the local directory (i.e. running python from build/Linux/RelWithDebInfo will result in `import onnxruntime` loading from build/Linux/RelWithDebInfo/onnxruntime) . 

Alternatively you can install the whl (should be in build/Linux/RelWithDebInfo/dist after you build the wheel) and `import onnxruntime` should work from anywhere, provided there isn't a subdirectory called onnxruntime.

Note: if you run python from the top level of the onnxruntime repository you created with `git clone` when you do `import onnxruntime` it will attempt to read from the 'onnxruntime' directory there - but that's the root of the source code and not the python package so you'll get errors about missing things.
